PATIENTS and officials at Steve Biko Academic Hospital woke up to flames on Monday, 30 May morning. Luckily, Gauteng health spokeswoman Kwara Kekana has said there were no patients or staff casualties reported due to the fire in the Tshwane hospital. “The Gauteng Department of Health can confirm that a fire broke out at Steve Biko Academic Hospital in the early hours of this morning. The fire which affected temporary structures at the facility was successfully put out by the Steve Biko Acamedic Hospital team, using the fire extinguishers on site. Thankfully, there were no patients or staff casualties,” she said.  “Eighteen patients and one corpse that were in separate temporary structures close to where the fire broke out had to be moved to other areas of the hospital as a safety precaution.” Kekana said the fire broke out about 1.20am at the Wendy house used as a temporary storage area for Covid-19 medical waste and an in-transit corpse area.  “It also affected a special temporary isolation unit and a tent used ‘for persons under investigation’. The affected structures were located outside the casualty area of the hospital. The cause of the fire is unknown at this stage,” said Kekana.